[Incidence rates of primary and secondary of syphilis reported annually in the United States declined dramatically in the 1940s to reach a low in 2000. After 2000, syphilis rates rebounded and continued to increase during 2005-2013, except for a brief plateau during 2009-2010 (http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm6318a4.htm). Increases have occurred primarily among men, and particularly among men who have sex with men (MSM). In the US in 2013, 75 percent of primary and secondary syphilis cases occur in MSM. This has been attributed to a variety of reasons that promote unprotected sex, such as engaging in sex only with partners perceived to have the same HIV status as one's own in an attempt to avoid using condoms (serosorting), taking pre-exposure (PrEP) or post-exposure HIV prophylaxis, use of psychoactive "party drugs," multiple anonymous sex partners, use of smartphone apps that facilitate anonymous "hookups," etc.

More information on the specific situation in Canton, NY from knowledgeable sources would be appreciated.

The finger stick test referred to in the news report above may be the test ProMED-mail recently posted (ProMED-mail post Syphilis - USA: rapid point-of-care test 20150112.3085761). It is a rapid (10 minutes) blood test for the detection of antibodies against _Treponema pallidum_ (the bacterium that causes syphilis) at the point-of-care (such as, doctors' offices, sexually transmitted diseases clinics), using finger stick blood samples. All positive tests should be followed up with further syphilis serological laboratory testing and clinical evaluation before final diagnosis (http://www.trinitybiotech.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Syphilis-Health-Check-Brochure.pdf). The test may be negative during the 1st few weeks of infection with _T. pallidum_.

ACR Health is a not-for-profit, community-based organization providing support services to individuals with chronic diseases, including HIV/AIDS in upstate New York (http://www.acrhealth.org/about/who-we-are).

New York State can be located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3726009,48297. Canton, with a population of 10 995 in 2010, is a town in St Lawrence County. Canton is the home of St Lawrence University, with about 2500 students, and the State University of New York at Canton, with over 3500 students. A map of New York State that shows the location of Canton can be found at https://www.google.com/maps/place/Canton,+NY+13617. - Mod.ML]
